ection of the bottom of the sea. Equipped with cameras, advanced sonar and bathymetric scanners, these ships mapped 125 square miles of the sea floor capturing a detailed dataset that allowed U.S. Geological Survey scientists to characterize the makeup of the sediment and bedrock in waters up to 92 meters deep.</p><p>While this research project was just <a href="https://www.usgs.gov/search?keywords=SeaBOSS&amp;ref=beautiful-public-data" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">one of many</a> such efforts to map the sea floor, it serves as a good example of what such data collection projects look like.</p><figure><iframe width="200" height="150" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/Yn6g1owPttc?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="" sandbox="allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups" loading="lazy"></iframe><figcaption>A timelapse of 834 photos of the sea floor collected by the USGS off the coast of Cape Ann, Massachusetts in 2004 and 2005. </figcaption></figure><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/QL5WoNgWLU08YkCGysawaEKLEQS0q5glZNzY8tdOT5s=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMi8xMi9GaWczXzAxLmpwZw==" alt="Mapping the Sea Floor" width="480" height="686" loading="lazy"/><figcaption>Photographs of the research vessels <em>Connecticut</em> (top) and <em>Ocean Explorer</em>, both used by the USGS for this mapping project.</figcaption></figure><p>Following a series of <a href="https://pubs.usgs.gov/of/2007/1373/html/imagepages/Fig3_02.html?ref=beautiful-public-data" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">predetermined survey lines</a>, the vessels cruised along at 5 knots and collected detailed bathymetry data (the actual shape and structure of the sea floor) from side-scan sonar and multi-beam echo sounders to create a &#34;high resolution chirp seismic reflection profile&#34; of the material beneath the seafloor, revealing the contours of sediment and bedrock.</p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/YDm8-eCo9YGxZrXplLqp0RHoVtads9KXI3_CXt3hNOU=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMi8xMi9iYWNrc2NhdHRlcl9zYW1wbGVzLnBuZw==" alt="Mapping the Sea Floor" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/wRR4w77eQcFAhXxMCUXHViY60uAThQMzhDuF-9GOzk8=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjIvMTIvYmFja3NjYXR0ZXJfc2FtcGxlcy5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/GkPJHdJY-m0C0wSKH-j2_Zorz0Dt6JqTRZ54sLT2pI0=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTAwMC8yMDIyLzEyL2JhY2tzY2F0dGVyX3NhbXBsZXMucG5n 1000w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ndLXCTfKHwjwazjc949QJ3vhobQQejls04JiFp5NndA=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTYwMC8yMDIyLzEyL2JhY2tzY2F0dGVyX3NhbXBsZXMucG5n 1600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/OFwV9YICZr1MP4FwJ0ZjTSaPrKIhbUAdcJQz8vw30dg=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MjQwMC8yMDIyLzEyL2JhY2tzY2F0dGVyX3NhbXBsZXMucG5n 2400w" loading="lazy"/><figcaption>An example of the &#34;high resolution chirp seismic reflection profiles&#34; of the sea floor captured by the research vessels using EdgeTech Geo-Star FSSB system and an SB-0512i towfish.</figcaption></figure><p>In addition to these advanced acoustic data collection tools, “ground validation” samples of sediments were collected at 87 locations, accompanied by a series of sea floor photographs and video sequences. Using the USGS’s <a href="https://pubs.usgs.gov/fs/fs142-00/fs142-00.pdf?ref=beautiful-public-data" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">SEAbed Observation and Sampling System</a> (SEABOSS), <a href="https://pubs.usgs.gov/of/2007/1373/html/appendix3.html?ref=beautiful-public-data" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">834 photographs</a> were taken as the SEABOSS unit drifted between 1 and 3 knots about a foot and a half above the sea floor. </p><p>In addition to an array of cameras and sensors, the instrument has a metal scoop that can be used to grab a sample of sand from the ocean floor for inspection upon ascent.</p><figure><iframe width="200" height="113" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/32aBMmESw7A?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="" sandbox="allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups" loading="lazy"></iframe><figcaption>A video from the USGS showing the SEABOSS instrument at work. </figcaption></figure><p>These photos capture a rich diversity of sea life. Lobsters, starfish, sharks, shrimp, skates and crabs all make appearances as well as some well disguised flounder blending in with the sandy bottom. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/mwDHAC1tAJGDNGF7sqYJzZomx5RFGhMJQZVN_YICTFw=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMi8xMi9GaWczXzAyXzY1MC5qcGc=" width="650" height="790" alt="Mapping the Sea Floor" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1aRTT10Y5VMoWFlOPFicZ4a427JtsG5milirnmLDJB4=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjIvMTIvRmlnM18wMl82NTAuanBn 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/mwDHAC1tAJGDNGF7sqYJzZomx5RFGhMJQZVN_YICTFw=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMi8xMi9GaWczXzAyXzY1MC5qcGc= 650w" loading="lazy"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/hiPnokJf7P99Hro1in1VVmBEy_BWuYYH0GVcAR1ymhc=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMi8xMi9waG90by1sb2NhdGlvbnMtc21hbGxlci0xLnBuZw==" alt="Mapping the Sea Floor" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_blHa9qp-cBmx-StfIBgVgSrulmFpOffI8NbUvoT4hM=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjIvMTIvcGhvdG8tbG9jYXRpb25zLXNtYWxsZXItMS5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/kNiyXLjdP7fxgn3flNFQ-LIxjoPz-uO9rf3kpow_B8E=/aHR0cH